For example, Fortnite or Ninja,
the best player in the world,

00:14:13.180 --> 00:14:15.125
played with Drake
JuJu Smith-Schuster

00:14:15.125 --> 00:14:17.920
and then a rapper, Travis
Scott, as I mentioned earlier,

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:23.200
had over 600,000 people
viewing it at the same time.

00:14:23.200 --> 00:14:26.240
Fashion is still really big
amongst today's young people.

00:14:26.240 --> 00:14:29.240
Streetwear reigns supreme.

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:31.840
Teens today differentiate
themselves in many ways.

00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:34.450
When it comes to fashion,
teens increasingly

00:14:34.450 --> 00:14:37.570
choose like streetwear
brands, like Supreme and Vans,

00:14:37.570 --> 00:14:40.630
over mainstream
brands, like Nike.

00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:43.630
Supreme has this particular
kind of outsider appeal

00:14:43.630 --> 00:14:46.910
for teenagers, even though
the brand launched in 1994,

00:14:46.910 --> 00:14:49.210
in New York City, as a
skateboarding and clothing

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:50.100
company.

00:14:50.100 --> 00:14:52.850
It caters to the skate
and hip hop cultures,

00:14:52.850 --> 00:14:55.270
and to just youth
cultures in general,

00:14:55.270 --> 00:14:59.890
and it's become an absolute
obsession for teenagers.

00:14:59.890 --> 00:15:04.360
When teens hear about
a new shoe or product

00:15:04.360 --> 00:15:07.870
launch on Reddit or other
social media, hundreds of teens

00:15:07.870 --> 00:15:10.720
will line up in New York to get
their hands on their product

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:11.980
before it sells out.

00:15:11.980 --> 00:15:13.540
And a lot of teens
are entrepreneurs.

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:15.070
They'll buy it
and then immediate

00:15:15.070 --> 00:15:19.370
flip it for extreme
markups, and big finance

00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:20.990
is starting to pay
attention to this.

00:15:20.990 --> 00:15:23.220
The Carlyle Group
invested in Supreme

00:15:23.220 --> 00:15:28.430
and valued the company at
over a billion dollars.

00:15:28.430 --> 00:15:31.500
We have no interest in
working at big companies.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:35.420
So most teens have
very little interest

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:37.940
in working for
major corporations,

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:41.230
even tech ones, like
Amazon and Facebook.

00:15:41.230 --> 00:15:43.730
They've seen their
parents and older siblings

00:15:43.730 --> 00:15:46.760
struggle in the workforce
and become unhappy,

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:49.400
despite these high paying jobs.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:52.190
Teens today are more
entrepreneurial than older

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:55.310
generations and have less
patience for bureaucratic work

00:15:55.310 --> 00:15:58.280
environments and crave
more independence.

00:15:58.280 --> 00:16:02.310
72% of them said they wanted to
start a business one day, which

00:16:02.310 --> 00:16:04.910
is pretty fascinating.

00:16:04.910 --> 00:16:08.780
Number nine, you've left us
with a big mess to clean up.

00:16:08.780 --> 00:16:11.240
Teens have grown
up watching reports

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:14.210
of a broken political
system, devastating climate

00:16:14.210 --> 00:16:17.624
change, mass shootings at
schools, homegrown terrorism,

00:16:17.624 --> 00:16:18.290
and ongoing war.

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:22.340
It's no surprise that like
68% of this generation

00:16:22.340 --> 00:16:24.300
feel the US is headed
in the wrong direction,

00:16:24.300 --> 00:16:27.410
and 44% are worried about the
way that things are going.

00:16:27.410 --> 00:16:30.590
This was more than any other
generation interviewed.

00:16:30.590 --> 00:16:36.150
And lastly, teens think that
we'll have a bigger impact

00:16:36.150 --> 00:16:37.640
than you think.

00:16:37.640 --> 00:16:40.160
It's easy for adults to
think that teens today

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:41.780
are pretty reckless.

00:16:41.780 --> 00:16:44.420
Much of what we read
or hear in the media

00:16:44.420 --> 00:16:47.210
focuses on the
negatives, like teens

00:16:47.210 --> 00:16:49.130
trying to pull off
crazy stunts on YouTube,

00:16:49.130 --> 00:16:51.530
which I'm sure you
have seen, or teens

00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:53.290
infatuation with the JUUL.

00:16:53.290 --> 00:16:57.650
Raise your hand if you've heard
of the JUUL, one person again.

00:16:57.650 --> 00:17:01.340
The JUUL is a sleek e-cigarette
that can be used indoors

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:03.850
without attracting attention.

00:17:03.850 --> 00:17:06.050
And don't get me wrong,
like the massive popularity

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:09.410
of this JUUL of e-cigarettes
is something that we

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:11.089
should be concerned about.

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:14.000
But the JUUL is something
that is massively

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:18.260
popular amongst teenagers,
but these types of behaviors

00:17:18.260 --> 00:17:21.680
are really not much
different than what we

00:17:21.680 --> 00:17:23.569
were like in prior generations.

00:17:23.569 --> 00:17:26.450
And one teen described it
as just like the generations

00:17:26.450 --> 00:17:29.870
before them, teens will always
want to rebel against the norm.

00:17:29.870 --> 00:17:30.787
We're not worse.

00:17:30.787 --> 00:17:32.870
It's just that you see it
more, because everything

00:17:32.870 --> 00:17:34.850
is being recorded.

00:17:34.850 --> 00:17:38.090
So focusing on these
negatives makes us lose

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:39.920
sight of the bigger picture.

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:43.730
What thousands of hours of
observing teens has shown me,

00:17:43.730 --> 00:17:47.180
what many studies show,
is that today's teens,

00:17:47.180 --> 00:17:50.210
they have a strong work
ethic and balance-forward

00:17:50.210 --> 00:17:53.370
thinking with old-school,
traditional values.

00:17:53.370 --> 00:17:55.490
So when adults think
about this new generation,

00:17:55.490 --> 00:17:56.990
we should be open-minded.

00:17:56.990 --> 00:18:03.770
Teens are multifaceted, and it's
going to take some time for us

00:18:03.770 --> 00:18:06.360
to like stick with a name
for this next generation.

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:07.760
But when I asked
teenagers, like,

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:10.070
tell me if you can
name your generation.

00:18:10.070 --> 00:18:11.030
What would you name it?

00:18:11.030 --> 00:18:12.863
Here were some of the
responses that I got--

00:18:12.863 --> 00:18:17.990
The Viral Generation, The
Founders, iGeneration,

00:18:17.990 --> 00:18:21.380
Digital Natives, Gen Mobile,
Generation Next, The Connected

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:23.480
Generation, et cetera.

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:25.694
So these were some of the names.

00:18:25.694 --> 00:18:27.110
These are some of
the names that I

00:18:27.110 --> 00:18:29.879
got when I asked a bunch of
teenagers, how would you--

00:18:29.879 --> 00:18:32.420
if you could name it, name your
generation, what would it be?

00:18:32.420 --> 00:18:35.510
But regardless of
what they're called,

00:18:35.510 --> 00:18:37.400
I think one thing
is really clear,

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:40.340
and that is that we
shouldn't underestimate

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:41.890
today's teenagers.

00:18:41.890 --> 00:18:44.330
Yes, they use phones
in different ways

00:18:44.330 --> 00:18:46.940
that we probably would
have never imagined.

00:18:46.940 --> 00:18:50.000
They idolize these esports
stars that we've never heard of,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:51.401
and they can be pretty quirky.

00:18:51.401 --> 00:18:53.900
But they're already showing us
that they're going to step up

00:18:53.900 --> 00:18:58.640
and tackle like major challenges
in ways that other generations

00:18:58.640 --> 00:18:59.570
haven't.

00:18:59.570 --> 00:19:02.130
Last weekend, like
March for Our Lives,

00:19:02.130 --> 00:19:05.120
was one example that was
organized by teenagers.

00:19:05.120 --> 00:19:09.170
It brought over 800,000
people to Washington DC

00:19:09.170 --> 00:19:12.500
and countless more to
hundreds of sister marches

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:13.700
across the country.

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:19.430
This is more than the Inaugural
Women's March, the Million Man

00:19:19.430 --> 00:19:24.770
March, and what else,
the March on Washington

00:19:24.770 --> 00:19:26.540
for Jobs and Freedom.

00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:30.020
800,000 was the
biggest march ever.

00:19:30.020 --> 00:19:34.160
And today's teens, they have
energy, they have passion,

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:36.080
and they have a
no-nonsense attitude

00:19:36.080 --> 00:19:39.420
about fixing the problems
that they've inherited.

00:19:39.420 --> 00:19:42.680
And if what they've
accomplished in the last month

00:19:42.680 --> 00:19:46.550
is any kind of
indication, we old people

00:19:46.550 --> 00:19:48.500
are in pretty good hands.

