Yesterday, we were with
a group of 80 teenagers,

00:25:04.640 --> 00:25:06.490
and we were looking
at their Snap scores.

00:25:06.490 --> 00:25:09.950
Snap score means when I send
one Snap message, I get a point.

00:25:09.950 --> 00:25:13.190
When I receive a Snap message,
I get an additional point.

00:25:13.190 --> 00:25:15.650
One teenager, and this was
kind of like the average,

00:25:15.650 --> 00:25:20.150
had over 600,000
points, which means

00:25:20.150 --> 00:25:23.204
the average was like she had
her Snapchat for a year or two

00:25:23.204 --> 00:25:24.370
or three or whatever it was.

00:25:24.370 --> 00:25:28.230
She was sending 14 snaps
an hour, 24 hours a day.

00:25:28.230 --> 00:25:32.630
So I think teens are very
self-aware that they're

00:25:32.630 --> 00:25:35.520
addicted to their phones,
but they don't really care.

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:38.630
I think when you go to
college, that's maybe

00:25:38.630 --> 00:25:40.130
when you start to
figure out, how

00:25:40.130 --> 00:25:42.440
do I manage my time
differently, and how can I

00:25:42.440 --> 00:25:45.050
be more productive?

00:25:45.050 --> 00:25:51.479
But today's teenagers are pretty
much like this all of the time.

00:25:51.479 --> 00:25:53.770
AUDIENCE: What do you think
teenagers' perception of VR

00:25:53.770 --> 00:25:54.635
is today?

00:25:54.635 --> 00:25:56.260
CORY LEVY: Teenagers'
perception of VR?

00:25:56.260 --> 00:26:00.490
I think some of the
longer tail of teenagers

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:04.300
are super interested
in it, and I

00:26:04.300 --> 00:26:08.110
think they'll be like the early
adopters to the technology.

00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:11.470
But the devices are expensive,
so it's kind of tough for them

00:26:11.470 --> 00:26:13.600
to get their hands on it.

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:16.810
But yeah, I think the
younger generations generally

00:26:16.810 --> 00:26:20.050
set those trends,
and I think VR will

00:26:20.050 --> 00:26:22.300
be really big amongst them.

00:26:22.300 --> 00:26:26.820
I think there's a question
to the right of you.

00:26:26.820 --> 00:26:29.560
AUDIENCE: I wanted to know a bit
more about the After School app

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:33.160
and how you think you won over
their trust to post things

00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:34.250
like you showed us.

00:26:34.250 --> 00:26:37.390
And also like how you
convince them that it's worth

00:26:37.390 --> 00:26:38.707
their time to spend on the app.

00:26:38.707 --> 00:26:40.290
CORY LEVY: Yeah, so
the first question

00:26:40.290 --> 00:26:42.610
on how we kind of
win over their trust.

00:26:42.610 --> 00:26:45.967
I think we built a
product for teenagers.

00:26:45.967 --> 00:26:47.050
Most people don't do that.

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:50.200
Most people just build
a product for everyone,

00:26:50.200 --> 00:26:54.000
and so our product was
built like just for them.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.670
So they know when they
download the app that there's

00:26:57.670 --> 00:26:59.170
a verification process.

00:26:59.170 --> 00:27:01.030
They need to get past
a few number of things

00:27:01.030 --> 00:27:03.400
to prove that they're a
teenager and that they

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:04.410
attend that high school.

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:06.370
So there's a level of
safety that they feel.

00:27:06.370 --> 00:27:07.870
Like, when I'm
joining this network,

00:27:07.870 --> 00:27:11.890
I had to jump through all these
hoops to prove I was a student,

00:27:11.890 --> 00:27:14.170
and so I think that
they like that.

00:27:14.170 --> 00:27:16.000
One high schooler was
telling me that they

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.820
posted some photo
on Facebook, and it

00:27:18.820 --> 00:27:20.260
was like to impress a girl.

00:27:20.260 --> 00:27:23.680
And the grandmother commented,
oh my god, you're so cute,

00:27:23.680 --> 00:27:27.380
and that was like the last
time he used Facebook.

00:27:27.380 --> 00:27:30.700
So I think people, teenagers,
are attracted to After School,

00:27:30.700 --> 00:27:32.020
because it's just for them.

00:27:32.020 --> 00:27:33.103
There are no grandparents.

00:27:33.103 --> 00:27:35.285
There are no teachers
on the platform,

00:27:35.285 --> 00:27:38.480
and it's a place where they
can just feel comfortable.

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:39.790
So yeah.

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:42.324
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the question
is how did you convince them

00:27:42.324 --> 00:27:43.240
it's worth their time?

00:27:43.240 --> 00:27:45.880
Like, they have a bunch of other
stuff going on in high school.

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:46.710
CORY LEVY: Yeah.

00:27:46.710 --> 00:27:47.780
That's a great question.

00:27:47.780 --> 00:27:49.905
How do we convince them
that it's worth their time?

00:27:49.905 --> 00:27:54.920
I don't have a perfect
answer to that question.

00:27:54.920 --> 00:27:58.400
Our app's grown 100%
through word of mouth.

00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:01.330
I think there's probably like
a really big demand needed

00:28:01.330 --> 00:28:02.930
for teenagers to
be in this place

00:28:02.930 --> 00:28:04.670
where it's just them
and their friends.

00:28:04.670 --> 00:28:07.310
We all had that, or at least I
had that when I was growing up.

00:28:07.310 --> 00:28:10.240
I had Facebook to go to
when I was in high school,

00:28:10.240 --> 00:28:14.110
and there were no teachers
or parents on Facebook.

00:28:14.110 --> 00:28:16.550
It was just me and my
high school buddies.

00:28:16.550 --> 00:28:19.390
So I think there is a big
demand to create a space where

00:28:19.390 --> 00:28:22.450
it's just them
and their friends,

00:28:22.450 --> 00:28:25.420
and Snapchat kind of helps
a little bit with that.

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:29.580
Although, parents are
joining Snap a lot right now.

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:32.320
But yeah, so I think just
creating that space just

00:28:32.320 --> 00:28:33.010
for them.

00:28:33.010 --> 00:28:34.240
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I just
had another question.

00:28:34.240 --> 00:28:35.781
Did they say anything
about when they

00:28:35.781 --> 00:28:39.220
think Snapchat is going to die
out or Instagram is going to?

00:28:39.220 --> 00:28:43.870
CORY LEVY: Yeah, so I think
there is this kind of circle

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:44.440
that we see.

00:28:44.440 --> 00:28:47.410
Where Facebook, they started
with the college audience.

00:28:47.410 --> 00:28:50.091
Their audience kind
of grew up, and then

00:28:50.091 --> 00:28:52.090
they started to build for
like a wider audience,

00:28:52.090 --> 00:28:54.250
and then, they neglected
their original audience.

00:28:54.250 --> 00:28:57.310
And neglected young
people, as they

00:28:57.310 --> 00:28:59.230
wanted to just gain
more users and get

00:28:59.230 --> 00:29:03.702
bigger numbers for investors
and their business.

00:29:03.702 --> 00:29:06.160
So I think we're starting to
see a little bit of that right

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:08.020
now with Instagram
and Snapchat, where

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:09.520
their parents and
their grandparents

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:11.530
are starting to join
those platforms.

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:16.150
That will drive the teens
out something different.

00:29:16.150 --> 00:29:19.180
Teens response to Instagram was,
well great, if my grandparents

00:29:19.180 --> 00:29:20.620
and parents are
on this, I'm just

00:29:20.620 --> 00:29:22.869
going to create this second
Instagram that they're not

00:29:22.869 --> 00:29:24.230
going to know about.

00:29:24.230 --> 00:29:28.090
With Snapchat, it's a
little bit harder to do,

00:29:28.090 --> 00:29:32.510
but with Snap's new update, if
y'all are familiar with that,

00:29:32.510 --> 00:29:34.900
that's like lowered the
engagement, I imagine,

00:29:34.900 --> 00:29:36.190
massively amongst teenagers.

00:29:36.190 --> 00:29:37.510
And the ones that I
talked to are like, yeah,

00:29:37.510 --> 00:29:39.610
with the new update, I
don't use Discover anymore.

00:29:39.610 --> 00:29:41.200
I don't-- they're on it less.

00:29:41.200 --> 00:29:44.410
So I'm not sure that was
the best update for Snapchat

00:29:44.410 --> 00:29:46.380
with respect to teenagers.

00:29:46.380 --> 00:29:49.600
AUDIENCE: So how do you prevent
the parents or grandparents

00:29:49.600 --> 00:29:51.134
to come to After School?

00:29:51.134 --> 00:29:53.050
CORY LEVY: So how do we
prevent the old people

00:29:53.050 --> 00:29:55.720
from infiltrating our network?

00:29:55.720 --> 00:29:57.370
Basically, it's a
verification process.

00:29:57.370 --> 00:29:59.730
So when you log
into the app, you

00:29:59.730 --> 00:30:04.390
show us you're school ID
or verify in a certain way.

00:30:04.390 --> 00:30:07.120
And that's similar to how
Facebook, when they started,

00:30:07.120 --> 00:30:10.644
you had to verify with
your dot edu address

00:30:10.644 --> 00:30:12.310
to prove that you are
a college student.

00:30:12.310 --> 00:30:16.090
We do things similar.

00:30:16.090 --> 00:30:19.660
AUDIENCE: So compared with this,
I feel that Google is so old.

00:30:19.660 --> 00:30:21.460
Do any of you--

00:30:21.460 --> 00:30:25.134
how many usage of your
audience actually use Google?

00:30:25.134 --> 00:30:26.800
CORY LEVY: How many
actually use Google?

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:29.260
Well, they love Google,
because it helps them

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:35.440
with their homework, but
yeah, its the default web

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:37.490
browser for them.

00:30:37.490 --> 00:30:40.344
So I think they're using
it from just probably how--

00:30:40.344 --> 00:30:42.260
or at least how I used
it in high school which

00:30:42.260 --> 00:30:45.482
was like if I want to know
anything, go to Google.

00:30:45.482 --> 00:30:46.690
It helps me with my homework.

00:30:46.690 --> 00:30:47.232
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:30:47.232 --> 00:30:49.231
CORY LEVY: And that's
probably, I would imagine,

00:30:49.231 --> 00:30:50.960
what they attribute
Google to the most

00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:54.820
is like the thing that
helps me with my homework.

00:30:54.820 --> 00:30:57.740
AUDIENCE: What's the one thing
that you believe about teens

00:30:57.740 --> 00:30:59.009
that nobody else believes?

00:30:59.009 --> 00:31:00.550
CORY LEVY: That
nobody else believes?

00:31:00.550 --> 00:31:03.180
Well, I think teenagers--

00:31:03.180 --> 00:31:05.950
I think adults think
teens are rebels,

00:31:05.950 --> 00:31:11.130
and I think that they're too
addicted to their phones.

00:31:11.130 --> 00:31:15.739
They're going to mess up
the whole next generation,

00:31:15.739 --> 00:31:16.780
and I disagree with that.

00:31:16.780 --> 00:31:21.250
I think that today's teenagers
are more capable than ever

00:31:21.250 --> 00:31:24.430
to make change, and
we're seeing examples

00:31:24.430 --> 00:31:29.890
of that with this March for
Our Lives demonstration.

00:31:29.890 --> 00:31:31.960
Just to say that like
a few teenagers planned

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:34.810
this massive rally, you
would have never thought

00:31:34.810 --> 00:31:37.240
that was possible five
years ago or ten years ago.

00:31:37.240 --> 00:31:40.280
But with social media, with
Twitter, with Facebook,

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:43.120
with Instagram, et
cetera, you're able to--

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:46.510
one kid in a school is able
to make this massive change.

00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:49.236
So I think this is like the
first really big example

00:31:49.236 --> 00:31:50.860
of this, but we're
going to see so much

00:31:50.860 --> 00:31:55.640
more of this in the days,
weeks, and years to come.

00:31:55.640 --> 00:31:57.570
So and I imagine
if you interviewed

00:31:57.570 --> 00:31:59.320
a bunch of old people,
they'd be like, no,

00:31:59.320 --> 00:32:02.200
they're definitely
not, but that's

00:32:02.200 --> 00:32:04.090
one thing I disagree with.

00:32:04.090 --> 00:32:06.250
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
if you could speak more

00:32:06.250 --> 00:32:09.830
to like the method of
collecting this information,

00:32:09.830 --> 00:32:12.160
and if you have any
tips that you've

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:17.200
learned from methods that
worked well versus others that

00:32:17.200 --> 00:32:18.889
might have been misleading.

00:32:18.889 --> 00:32:21.180
CORY LEVY: To collect this
information about teenagers?

00:32:21.180 --> 00:32:21.520
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:23.485
CORY LEVY: Yeah, so
that's a great question.

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:28.780
Teenagers have
different personas.

00:32:28.780 --> 00:32:31.300
They're around their friends,
it's one way they act.

00:32:31.300 --> 00:32:34.340
When they're around adults,
they act incredibly different.

00:32:34.340 --> 00:32:40.000
So it's really challenging
to get real, true information

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:41.140
about teenagers.

00:32:41.140 --> 00:32:43.300
So a couple of ways we
do it is, one, we luckily

00:32:43.300 --> 00:32:46.900
have this app that millions of
teenagers are communicating on.

00:32:46.900 --> 00:32:49.360
So we're able to pick
up trends in language

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:52.779
that they're using just from
the posts that they write.

00:32:52.779 --> 00:32:54.820
Additionally, we have like
a bunch of ambassadors

00:32:54.820 --> 00:32:59.320
across America, and we
ask them to help us.

00:32:59.320 --> 00:33:01.150
Hey, text this to your friend.

00:33:01.150 --> 00:33:03.820
Text these questions
to your friends.

00:33:03.820 --> 00:33:06.280
Take a screen shot
of the people you

00:33:06.280 --> 00:33:08.860
follow, the people you
subscribe to on YouTube,

00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:13.020
so we can see like who
the big vloggers are.

00:33:13.020 --> 00:33:14.890
So it's really tough.

00:33:14.890 --> 00:33:18.640
Sometimes, we'll get adult
answers from teenagers,

00:33:18.640 --> 00:33:21.310
and they'll be like
a capital letter.

00:33:21.310 --> 00:33:25.350
They'll speak very formally, and
then other times, we'll get--

00:33:27.910 --> 00:33:28.720
let's see.

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:31.490
I think I maybe put--

00:33:31.490 --> 00:33:33.670
well, I guess I capitalized
most of the things,

00:33:33.670 --> 00:33:35.800
but like the way that
kids are replying to me.

00:33:35.800 --> 00:33:37.570
You could tell it was like
they're doing this like they're

00:33:37.570 --> 00:33:38.778
texting one of their friends.

00:33:38.778 --> 00:33:42.190
It's like totally incorrect
grammar, misspellings

00:33:42.190 --> 00:33:42.829
everywhere.

00:33:42.829 --> 00:33:45.370
And that's kind of one of the
indications of like, all right,

00:33:45.370 --> 00:33:47.320
this person is being
really real versus

00:33:47.320 --> 00:33:49.530
if they were typing like
real professionally,

00:33:49.530 --> 00:33:52.195
but yeah, it's hard.

00:33:52.195 --> 00:33:54.250
It's really, really hard.

00:33:54.250 --> 00:33:56.386
People are biased,
but yeah, in short,

00:33:56.386 --> 00:33:57.760
a couple of things
that we do is,

00:33:57.760 --> 00:33:59.830
one, we use our own
platform, and two,

00:33:59.830 --> 00:34:01.390
we have a group of
teen ambassadors

00:34:01.390 --> 00:34:03.590
that will go and ask
the questions for us.

00:34:03.590 --> 00:34:05.830
So it's a teenager
talking to a teen,

00:34:05.830 --> 00:34:08.580
not an old person
talking to a teen.

00:34:08.580 --> 00:34:10.964
AUDIENCE: So one question,
what happens after graduation

00:34:10.964 --> 00:34:12.130
to the After School account?

00:34:12.130 --> 00:34:13.780
CORY LEVY: For After School,
what happens after graduation

00:34:13.780 --> 00:34:14.950
is they're kicked out.

00:34:14.950 --> 00:34:16.699
Eventually, we'll build
a college product,

00:34:16.699 --> 00:34:21.239
but to keep the network
just high schoolers,

00:34:21.239 --> 00:34:22.280
we have to kick them out.

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:25.440
So we've kicked out
a million plus users.

00:34:25.440 --> 00:34:26.903
One last question.

00:34:26.903 --> 00:34:29.218
AUDIENCE: Do you
see-- so you said

00:34:29.218 --> 00:34:31.070
that there was some
entrepreneurial spirit

00:34:31.070 --> 00:34:33.413
among the teenagers, some
of the selling slimes.

00:34:33.413 --> 00:34:35.868
That's probably why my
daughter is learning to smile

00:34:35.868 --> 00:34:38.323
and is only eight years old.

00:34:38.323 --> 00:34:42.742
Did you see any promising
entrepreneurial spirit

00:34:42.742 --> 00:34:46.179
like some ideas a teenager--

00:34:46.179 --> 00:34:48.598
CORY LEVY: Yeah, so
her question was,

00:34:48.598 --> 00:34:50.139
she has an 8-year-old
daughter that's

00:34:50.139 --> 00:34:51.810
making slime and selling it.

00:34:51.810 --> 00:34:55.989
And is this generation-- do I
see any ideas from teenagers

00:34:55.989 --> 00:34:58.195
that are trying to make change?

00:34:58.195 --> 00:34:59.542
And I see it every day.

00:34:59.542 --> 00:35:00.250
It's really cool.

00:35:00.250 --> 00:35:02.830
There's one 18-year-old
that I'm working

00:35:02.830 --> 00:35:07.435
with that's trying to make
vegan chicken nuggets to make

00:35:07.435 --> 00:35:08.500
us all be vegetarians.

00:35:08.500 --> 00:35:10.480
And trying to build
like a teen brand

00:35:10.480 --> 00:35:14.840
and make being a
vegetarian cool.

00:35:14.840 --> 00:35:18.280
And yeah, so that's just one
example of a teenager being

00:35:18.280 --> 00:35:20.720
like this is a real problem.

00:35:20.720 --> 00:35:23.380
And he's taking matters
into his own hands

00:35:23.380 --> 00:35:30.040
and trying to create the vegan
version of McDonald's, and I've

00:35:30.040 --> 00:35:32.170
seen that dozens of times.

00:35:32.170 --> 00:35:34.490
So it's inspiring.

00:35:34.490 --> 00:35:36.850
Thank you all for listening,
and hopefully, you're

00:35:36.850 --> 00:35:39.620
a little bit more knowledge
on today's teenager.

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:43.570
[APPLAUSE]

